 England":"Sussex, England","Of, Radynden, Sussex, England":"Sussex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Radynden, Sussex, England":"Sussex, England"},"en":{"1284–":"1284–Deceased","1274–1350":"1274–1350","1306–Female":"1306–Deceased","1310–Female":"1310–Deceased","1316–1401":"1316–1401","1284–Female":"1284–Deceased","1274":"1274","1284":"1284","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","Abt 1306":"about 1306","1290":"1290","1316":"1316","1315":"1315","1401":"1401","about 1305":"about 1305","about 1316":"about 1316","Abt 1310":"about 1310","1310":"1310","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1306":"1306","Radinden, Sussex, England":"Sussex, England, United Kingdom","Sussex, England":"Sussex, England","Of, Radynden, Sussex, England":"Sussex, England, United Kingdom","Radynden, Sussex, England":"Sussex, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":6,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705191,"age":31,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705192,"age":44,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705195,"age":98,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Joan was born in 1284, in Sussex, England. She married John de Radynden about 1305, in Sussex, England. They were the parents of at least 3 daughters. She died in her hometown."},"et":{"1284–":"1284–Surnud","1274–1350":"1274–1350","1306–Female":"1306–Surnud","1310–Female":"1310–Surnud","1316–1401":"1316–1401","1284–Female":"1284–Surnud","1274":"1274","1284":"1284","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","Abt 1306":"umbes 1306","1290":"1290","1316":"1316","1315":"1315","1401":"1401","about 1305":"umbes 1305","about 1316":"umbes 1316","Abt 1310":"umbes 1310","1310":"1310","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1306":"1306","Radinden, Sussex, England":"Sussex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Sussex, England":"Sussex, England","Of, Radynden, Sussex, England":"Sussex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Radynden, Sussex, England":"Sussex, England"},"fi":{"1284–":"1284–Kuollut","1274–1350":"1274–1350","1306–Female":"1306–Kuollut","1310–Female":"1310–Kuollut","1316–1401":"1316–1401","1284–Female":"1284–Kuollut","1274":"1274","1284":"1284","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","Abt 1306":"noin 1306","1290":"1290","1316":"1316","1315":"1315","1401":"1401","about 1305":"noin 1305","about 1316":"noin 1316","Abt 1310":"noin 1310","1310":"1310","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1306":"1306","Radinden, Sussex, England":"Sussex, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Sussex, England":"Sussex, England","Of, Radynden, Sussex, England":"Sussex, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Radynden, Sussex, England":"Sussex, England"},"fr":{"1284–":"1284–Décédée","1274–1350":"1274–1350","1306–Female":"1306–Décédée","1310–Female":"1310–Décédée","1316–1401":"1316–1401","1284–Female":"1284–Décédée","1274":"1274","1284":"1284","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","Abt 1306":"environ 1306","1290":"1290","1316":"1316","1315":"1315","1401":"1401","about 1305":"environ 1305","about 1316":"environ 1316","Abt 1310":"environ 1310","1310":"1310","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1306":"1306","Radinden, Sussex, England":"Sussex, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Sussex, England":"Sussex, Angleterre","Of, Radynden, Su